<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-171-700  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 171 700.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Feb 5 1990 n256 p48(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The efficient frontier. (FMC Corp.'s five-year-old merger of itsdata centers pays off)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Forsythe, Jason.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>FMC Corp's 1984 merger of its data centers has paid off bydecreasing operations costs, systems requirements and programmingstaffs.andP;  FMC is a highly diversified $3.5 billion conglomeratethat produces industrial machinery and defense equipment.andO;According to an executive at Nolan, Norton andamp; Co, the Chicago-basedinformation management consulting firm, there are three reasonsfor FMC's success.andP;  First, FMC's long commitment to rewriteapplications for automated tape operations and tape mounts is nowpaying off.andP;  Second, FMC is careful to test new equipmentthoroughly prior to production.andP;  Third, FMC pays close attentionto costs and to the acquisition and disposition of equipment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   FMC Corp. (management).andO;Ticker:    FMC.andO;Topic:     Information CentersProfit AnalysisEfficiencyOrganization StructureStrategic Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphphotograph.andO;Caption:   FMC's Dallas data center. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>